{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584632"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:51:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:51:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14754"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14754"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.09,0.74,0.05,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114047"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7445"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96062"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4939"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5189"},{"type":"tags","id":"10150"},{"type":"tags","id":"10293"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18222"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21691"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114047","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114047"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to her general practitioner with difficulty falling asleep. She works as a night shift nurse and struggles to sleep during daylight hours, even when wearing an eye mask. She reports feeling constantly tired and has trouble maintaining a regular sleep schedule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe doctor discusses sleep hygiene and considers prescribing melatonin to help regulate her sleep cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of melatonin?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activates gamma-aminobutyric acid receptors","Blocks histamine H1 receptors","Binds to MT1 and MT2 receptors","Inhibits serotonin reuptake","Blocks dopamine D2 receptors"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMelatonin primarily works by \u003Cstrong\u003Ebinding to MT1 and MT2 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E in the brain, particularly the suprachiasmatic nucleus. This helps regulate circadian rhythms and promote sleep onset. Melatonin is particularly useful for shift workers and those with jet lag as it helps reset the circadian rhythm when taken at the desired sleep time.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivating gamma-aminobutyric acid receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of benzodiazepines and \u0027z-drugs\u0027, whilst \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking histamine H1 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E explains the sedating effects of first-generation antihistamines. \u003Cstrong\u003EInhibiting serotonin reuptake\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocking dopamine D2 receptors\u003C/strong\u003E is how antipsychotic medications work. Melatonin has fewer side effects compared to other sleep medications and is not associated with dependence or tolerance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Melatonin is synthesised from serotonin in the pineal gland primarily during darkness.","Melatonin secretion is inhibited by exposure to light via the retinohypothalamic tract.","Melatonin acts via MT1 and MT2 receptors to regulate sleep-wake cycles and circadian rhythm."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Australian Medicines Handbook (online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from: https://amhonline.amh.net.au/","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al. Rang and Dale\u0027s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96062"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14754"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96062","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96062"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-14T22:48:18+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-14T22:48:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7445"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114047"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4930"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Nervous System","s